Depends on https://github.com/crewAIInc/crewAI-tools/pull/345 - we have to wait cut crewai-tools

Now within a CrewBase you can select muliples tools per agent, like:

```python
@agent
    def mathematician(self) -> Agent:
        return Agent(
            config=self.agents_config['mathematician'], # type: ignore[index]
            verbose=True,
            tools=self.get_mcp_tools("multiply", "divide", "calc_tool")
        )
```


https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/efe8bd4d-6eed-4578-aed4-2501aead9b43

Closes https://github.com/crewAIInc/crewAI/issues/1790, https://github.com/crewAIInc/crewAI/issues/2678, https://github.com/crewAIInc/crewAI/issues/2464

This PR addressed a couple of issues:
1. The sources must not be added while initializing the Knowledge otherwise we could not reset it
2. Crew instances can now be discovered from any function or method with a return type annotation of `-> Crew`, as well as from module-level attributes assigned to a Crew instance. Additionally, crews can be retrieved from within a Flow
3. We can now reset memory from multiples Crews

Here is some way that become be able to discovery a Crew:

### From Flow
```python
class MyFlow(Flow):
    @start()
    def start(self) -> Crew: # <---- This instance will be fetched
        return Crew(
            agents=[agent],
            tasks=[task],
            verbose=True,
            memory=True,
        )

    @listen(start)
    def generate_fun_fact(self, crew):
        crew.kickoff(inputs={"question": "What is the user's name?"})


class MyFlow(Flow):
    @start()
    def start(self) -> Crew:
        ....

    @listen(start)
    def generate_crew(self, output) -> Crew: # <---- This instance will be fetched
        return Crew(
            agents=[agent],
            tasks=[task],
            verbose=True,
            memory=True,
        )

    @listen(generate_fun_fact)
    def any_method(self, crew) -> Crew:
        crew.kickoff(inputs={"question": "What is the user's name?"})


    @listen(any_method)
    def generate_another_crew(self, output) -> Crew: # <---- This instance will be fetched
        return Crew(
            agents=[agent],
            tasks=[task],
            verbose=True,
            memory=True,
        )

    @listen(generate_fun_fact)
    def another_method(self, crew) -> Crew:
        crew.kickoff(inputs={"question": "What is the user's name?"})
```

### From a python script

From this example we’ll be able to retrieve all three Crew instances

```python
# crew.py

import ...

crew_one = Crew(
    agents=[agent],
    tasks=[task],
    verbose=True,
    process=Process.sequential,
    knowledge_sources=[
        string_source
    ],  # Enable knowledge by adding the sources here. You can also add more sources to the sources list.
) # <---- This instance will be fetched

crew_two = Crew(
    agents=[agent],
    tasks=[task],
    verbose=True,
    process=Process.sequential,
    knowledge_sources=[
        string_source
    ],  # Enable knowledge by adding the sources here. You can also add more sources to the sources list.
) # <---- This instance will be fetched

def create_crew(): Crew <---- This instance will be feetched
    return Crew(
        agents=[agent],
        tasks=[task],
        verbose=True,
        process=Process.sequential,
        knowledge_sources=[
        string_source
    ],  # Enable knowledge by adding the sources here. You can also add more sources to the sources list.
)
```

### From CrewBase

Support remains the same, still required use `crew()` method name

```python
@CrewBase
class OtherExample:
   @crew
    def crew(self) -> Crew: # <---- This instance will be fetched
       return Crew(
            agents=self.agents,  # Automatically created by the @agent decorator
            tasks=self.tasks,  # Automatically created by the @task decorator
            process=Process.sequential,
            verbose=True,
            memory=True,
            knowledge_sources=[
                StringKnowledgeSource(
                    content="Users name is John. He is 30 years old and lives in San Francisco."
                )
            ],
            # process=Process.hierarchical, # In case you wanna use that instead https://docs.crewai.com/how-to/Hierarchical/
        )
```
